text: Pros...  - Mew's casting.  - Obi Wan's casting.  - Canary's cleavage.   Cons...  - Harley looks beyond awful. Her Squad outfit wasn't great but it was vastly better than this glittery garbage fire. It's asinine that they didn't even try and use her iconic colors or ANYTHING.  - The film looks to be a Harley Quinn &......... friends film instead of a legitimate BOP film. By doing this, the other BOP characters don't get done justice and Gotham City Sirens fans who wanted Harley on her own more villainous & sexy team don't get appeased either. The only people this safe "heroic" so random Harley & friends bullshit appeals to are prude twitter feminist who don't give a shit about BOP, they just want to use Harley as a absurd feminist iconic for leaving the Joker. (to be clear I don't have a problem with feminism, just modern Internet brand outrage prone woke feminism)  - Cass Cain resembling her character in zero ways whatsoever and not just visually. In the comics she is basically River Tam from Serenity who is so profoundly badass she could probably beat Batman hand to hand and yet here she is a wisecracking out of shape little brat.  - Canary not having her fishnets (but they gave it to harley for the Roller Dirby???)  - Black Mask... not having a Black Fucking Mask.

This looks far more appealing to me than some more cookie cutter family friendly content that we've seen a million times before.    (also Harley Quinn is one of the most marketable DC characters, no shit they'll use her to sell the movie. I REALLY, *REALLY* want to root for DC films but it seems like the studio goes through comments and reviews and picks ONE THING from those reviews... then they put ALL their energy and focus on whatever that one, single thing is. For instance, people really liked the Wonder Woman film, so the studio pumps the Justice League film FULL of Wonder Woman scenes, to the point of actually neglecting other characters. And although audiences weren't crazy about the first Suicide Squad film, they really liked Harley Quinn, so what does the studio do?? They make the next film ALL ABOUT. So far I've seen very few images of the other characters which makes me worried that this film will be an overdose of Harley...which isn't necessarily a BAD thing, but based on the way things have been handled so far, it makes me uneasy.

text: I'm not sure how to feel about this movie... on the one hand I love Harley Quinn, I thought Margot did a great job bringing her to life in Suicide Squad.    I also loved Harley in Batman TAS, and I don't have much exposure to her outside of those 2 things, but I am aware of her goings on via fan groups and nerd discussions, so I know about her on and off relationship with Ivy, and I know about the popularity of the Harley  comics which put a big spotlight focus on Harley and her exploits(naturally)...  With all that said, I feel like, with my light knowledge of the Harley comics, this movie is seemingly authentic to the art style of the comics, with all the crazy pastel colors and Harley's "new look", and all that, but maybe for the same reason I've never cared to delve into the Harley comics, this movie just doesn't seem to pull me in at all... which confuses me because I like the character, and I love Ewan Mcgregor as an actor...  Maybe it's the fact that I've been conditioned to take movies with too much emphasis on "girl power", "diversity" or other SJW nonsense that's kinda keeping my interest at bay... I mean I'm totally gonna watch this, I give every movie a fair shot regardless of how uninterested I am in it.  So i'll keep my judgement of it until after I've gotten a chance to watch it, but so far I have to say, I'm very underwhelmed... I mean as I said, I'm not the BIGGEST fan of Harley, but I do enjoy the character and Margot's portrayal of her, but this movie just seems "Meh..." to me in the same way that the show Gotham always seemed "Meh..." to me...  I hope it's great, but so far, there's nothing that's got me excited in the slightest... I'm far more excited for Joker... like BY A LOT.

text: Nothing is more pathetic than people who want to ruin a character because they can't stand reality. Harley Quinn is about the realities of abuse, this idea that every female character has to stand up and kick ass is the exact same level of pathetic as thinking they should all be damsels in distress, because that's what you are making them by implying all female characters need to be saved. It's limits female characters, it prevents them from being complete and complex characters and turns them into a pathetic fantasy escape for people who can't handle the fact that women are just people, with the same flaws and unhappy endings. They're still defined by men, their entire movies, their entire existence, is defined by men, and they are laughing stock of every man and woman who doesn't give a fuck about what the other sex wants, rebelling against something is as pathetic as pandering to it, both make you secondary to people who couldn't give a fuck about you.  They're doing their own thing, barely aware of your existence, and you are still letting them define who you are.  This is why people HATE "strong female characters", because they're never strong, they're always examples of pathetic weakness, and an insecure pathological need to paint themselves and all other women as victims. Strong women don't do that shit, strong women just are, they are themselves, without insulting, or copying, or fighting, or rebelling, against men.

text: I can see where they are trying to go with Harley Quinn... almost like evolving her into a much closer to the Animated series character, than she first appeared in Suicide Squad... But, and I know this is just the trailer, but I felt like Margot was a bit shakey. Especially on the accent. Some parts of the accent she nailed, and others it was like her regular voice slipped through. If those are final scenes, I personally probably would have called cut to try it again, so I would be surprised those made it. She was also a bit shakey on her delivery... it didn't seem natural.   And I am personally finding it hard to suspend my disbelief that she is Harley Quinn. To me it seems like she is fighting against the accent, and also failing to get the timing right on the things she says or does. Which makes me kind of worried for this movie.. especially since, lets be honest, she is the main attraction here.

text: Holy shit, they really fucked over the other female characters to try making Harley standout/look good.  Each one of them has a really cool or unique costume in the comics.  Huntress and Montoya (the question) have one of the most unique costumes  in DC with a great colour palette in contrast to Harley. Here they all  have dark boring/drab costumes, Montoya has the most stand out costume  but standing next to Harley the stark comparison drowns out almost all  uniqueness.  And what the hell did they do to poor Cassandra? She was a badass  warrior and one of the most beloved batgirls. Here it looks like they  made her into the submissive Asian female stereo type to be saved to  make Harley look good.   Not to mention that while Harley looks like she came from a superhero  movie, Cassandra looks like she is on her way to shoot the remake of the  goonies.  And I don't want to hear any bullshit that this is supposed to be set in  a more "grounded" universe considering this is a sequel to a movie  where a Mexican fire God, an assassin with a bright red and white  costume, a mentally unstable girl, a crocodile man who loves watching  BET in the sewers and an Australian hooligan using boomerangs stopped an  Egyptian goddess, her zombie horde and her cgi brother from ending the  world by swinging her hips.

text: This sounded fun, but it looks even worse than Suicide Squad. Clearly not one person involved has any familiarity with the source material, let alone the passion to make sure the film does it justice.   Also, I cannot understand why so many people love Margot Robbie's Harley Quinn. She's not as true to the source material as I would like, and the only thing more fake and cringy than her acting is her abysmal attempt to do Harley's iconic voice. It feels like she's so focused on trying to force the voice, slowly spitting the words out and over-anunciating, in a very strange tone that sounds nothing like Harley's iconic high-pitched voice, that the voice and the acting comes across as forced, wooden, methodical, and tired. Harley should have much more light, energy, carelessness, and speed to her, and you need to see that crazy look in her eyes. Harley is almost childlike; she is very raw, emotional, and authentic. She is far from reality. Harley Quinn doesn't ACT crazy, she IS crazy. This version just feels like an awful impression rolled in Hot Topic, but everyone loves it because she's hot and popular.

text: *sigh* I'm still underwhelmed and not impressed. I like the original Harley Quinn in Batman the animated series, she was intelligent, but quirky and suffered schizophrenia and Stockholm syndrome. Only turned to crime and violence to impress and get validation from the Joker.  Now in live-action we get a cookie-cutter "crazy bitch bad girl" that looks almost nothing like the original character and more like a superficial try-hard pop music singer/imitation of Gwen Stafani *acting* "crazy" and "edgy". I'm not impressed at all by this portrayal and the movie doesn't look all that great so far. I was vastly more impressed with Wonder Woman and Shazam! I would *not* pay $ to see this. text: While I am not too crazy about movies where the lead role is played by a women. I have to say I am looking forward to this one. Probably more so then other super hero movies. Their was something about her and her role in Suicide Squad that was just perfect. Maybe its because I'm a guy and she was pretty sexy in it. Maybe it how unique and twisted her character was. But she was perfect for the roll. I'm not a comic book guy, so I couldn't tell you much of anything aside from what I see in the movies or from what some of my friends tell me, or news snippets and such. But I do know she did this roll perfect which left allot of us crazing for more.  I am really hoping she makes the Joker look like a joke in this new movie. And while like many others, I did not feel the Joker in Suicide Squad was done right at all, I still appreciate it on some level. I haven't seen the new Joker movie yet, but I have been enjoying the different Jokers along the way. However I do which they could stick with one version, one movie, and just continue a story, not redue it after each movie or two.   Either way, I am looking forward to seeing this. IT looks very promising. And I hope they didn't change her character too much as it was perfect in suicide squad.

I also really like how Harley has replaced Barbara Gordon in this movie. I have never liked Barbara Gordon and I like her even less ever since we got the New 52 and Rebirth. The only concern I have is how they're going to portray Cassandra Cain. She's my favorite Batgirl and while I am happy they have cast an actress who kind of looks like her, (she's not exactly how I pictured Cass, but I can let it go since they're at least trying to be accurate to how the character looks in the comics, especially if she's a good actress), I fear that they won't portray Cass's character correctly seeing as she is quite possibly the biggest badass on the planet who is a nearly unbeatable fighter, reads body langauge and couldn't speak until she was in her late teens due to a psychic's intervention, and was trained to be an assassin from the time she was born due to being the daughter of David Cain and Lady Shiva. I'm so happy they are doing Harley the justice she deserves, I just hope they don't do my girl Cass dirty.

The villian was really over the top, but fun and the new characters are great. The style of the film is gorgeous and really in tone with Harley Quinn and the Birds of Prey. A couple downsides is that I found the female Police Officer kinda of uninteresting and there didn't feel there was a real sense of threat compared to previous DC films.
